# Frontend Standards

## Pages

Five pages. No more, no less.

| Page | File | Data source |
|---|---|---|
| About / Hero | `pages/About.tsx` | `/api/profile`, `/api/profile/photo` |
| Experience | `pages/Experience.tsx` | `/api/experience` |
| Skills | `pages/Skills.tsx` | `/api/skills` |
| Education | `pages/Education.tsx` | `/api/education` |
| Pipeline Health | `pages/PipelineHealth.tsx` | `/api/pipeline` |

## Component Rules

- One component per file, named export — no default exports
- Pages are thin: data fetching + layout only. Logic goes in hooks.
- Extract a component when it is used in **more than one place**. Not before.
- If a component file is getting long, the component is probably doing too much.

```tsx
// ✅ correct — named export
export function ExperienceCard({ job }: { job: CareerEvent }) { ... }

// ❌ wrong — default export makes refactoring harder
export default function ExperienceCard(...) { ... }
```

## Types

All API response types live in `src/types.ts`. They mirror the shapes in `data_models.md` exactly. Do not define inline types for API responses — reference `types.ts`.

```ts
// src/types.ts — single source of truth for API shapes
export interface CareerEvent {
  id: string;
  company: string;
  title: string;
  start_date: string;
  end_date: string | null;
  responsibilities: string[];
  key_projects: KeyProject[];
  source: 'json' | 'firebase';
}
```

## Data Fetching

Simple `useEffect` + `useState` per page. No external data-fetching library.
The data is static after page load — there is no need for caching, invalidation, or background refetch.

**No mock data, ever.** The frontend makes real fetch calls from day one. Before the pipeline runs, pages render their loading/empty states. When the pipeline completes and DuckDB is populated, content appears — that moment is the end-to-end proof the system works. Hardcoded data would mask that signal.

```tsx
// ✅ correct — real fetch, proper loading state
const [experience, setExperience] = useState<CareerEvent[] | null>(null);
useEffect(() => {
  fetch('/api/experience')
    .then(r => r.json())
    .then(setExperience);
}, []);

if (!experience) return <Loader />;
if (experience.length === 0) return <Text c="dimmed">Pipeline hasn't run yet.</Text>;
```

No Redux. No Zustand. No React Query. The data is read-only and fetched once.

## Styling

Use `BP` constants from `theme.ts` for colours/spacing. Pages may use inline `style` with `BP` (BattlePlan layout). Prefer Mantine `Text`, `Stack`, etc. for typography. No ad-hoc hex outside `theme.ts`.

```tsx
// ✅ correct — uses Mantine
<Text size="sm" c="dimmed">{job.title}</Text>

// ❌ wrong — inline style
<p style={{ fontSize: '14px', color: '#888' }}>{job.title}</p>
```

## No Unnecessary Abstraction

Do not create wrapper components around single Mantine components just to rename them.
Do not create a `Button.tsx` that just re-exports Mantine's `Button`.
Do not create a `theme/index.ts` that re-exports tokens that Mantine already owns.
